{"parse":{"title":"Three-language formula","pageid":16655007,"revid":856505982,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>The <b>three-language formula</b> for language learning was formulated in 1968 by the <a href=\"/wiki/Ministry_of_Human_Resource_Development\" title=\"Ministry of Human Resource Development\">Ministry of Education</a> of the <a href=\"/wiki/Government_of_India\" title=\"Government of India\">Government of India</a> in consultation with the states. The formula as enunciated in the 1968 National Policy Resolution which provided for the study of \"Hindi, English and modern Indian language (preferably one of the southern languages) in the Hindi speaking states and Hindi, English and the Regional language in the non-Hindi speaking States\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-nic_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-nic-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The formula was formulated in response to demands from non-Hindi speaking states of the <a href=\"/wiki/South_India\" title=\"South India\">South</a>, such as <a href=\"/wiki/Karnataka\" title=\"Karnataka\">Karnataka</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Andhra_Pradesh\" title=\"Andhra Pradesh\">Andhra Pradesh</a> and mainly <a href=\"/wiki/Tamil_Nadu\" title=\"Tamil Nadu\">Tamil Nadu</a>. Currently, the three language system is not followed in Tamil Nadu due to efforts of former Chief Minister <a href=\"/wiki/C._N._Annadurai\" title=\"C. N. Annadurai\">C. N. Annadurai</a>.\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#History\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">History</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Criticism\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Criticism</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#External_links\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">External links</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"History\">History</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Three-language_formula&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: History\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The first recommendation for a three-language policy was made by the <a href=\"/wiki/University_Grants_Commission_(India)\" title=\"University Grants Commission (India)\">University Education Commission</a> in 1948\u201349, which did not find the requirement to study three languages to be an extravagance, citing the precedents of the Netherlands and Switzerland. While accepting that <a href=\"/wiki/Hindi\" title=\"Hindi\">Hindi</a> was itself a minority language, and had no superiority over others such as <a href=\"/wiki/Kannada_language\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Kannada language\">Kannada</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Telugu_language\" title=\"Telugu language\">Telugu</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Tamil_language\" title=\"Tamil language\">Tamil</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Marathi_language\" title=\"Marathi language\">Marathi</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Bengali_language\" title=\"Bengali language\">Bengali</a>,  <a href=\"/wiki/Punjabi_language\" title=\"Punjabi language\">Punjabi</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Urdu\" title=\"Urdu\">Urdu</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Gujarati_language\" title=\"Gujarati language\">Gujarati</a> all of which had a longer history and greater body of literature, the commission still foresaw Hindi as eventually replacing English as the means by which every province may participate in Federal functions.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The Education Commission of 1965\u201366 recommended a modified or graduated three-language formula. Following some debate, the original three-language formula was adopted by the <a href=\"/wiki/India_Parliament\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"India Parliament\">India Parliament</a> in 1968.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Weinstein_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Weinstein-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> The 1986 National Policy on Education reiterated the 1968 formula.<sup id=\"cite_ref-nic_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-nic-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In 1972 the government launched a committee for promotion of Urdu under the chairmanship of <a href=\"/wiki/I._K._Gujral\" title=\"I. K. Gujral\">I. K. Gujral</a>. The committee's 1975 report recommended safeguards for significant (i.e. greater than 10 percent) Urdu-speaking minorities which included the use of Urdu for official purposes and as a medium of instruction. Following consideration of the report by the Cabinet in 1979, and by the Taraqqui-e-Urdu Board from 1979 to 1983, modified proposals from the Gujral committee were passed on to the state governments in 1984.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>A new committee of experts was launched in 1990 under the chairmanship of <a href=\"/wiki/Ali_Sardar_Jafri\" title=\"Ali Sardar Jafri\">Ali Sardar Jafri</a> to  examine implementation of the Gujral committee recommendations. This committee recommended modifying the three-language formula to \"In Hindi speaking States: (a) Hindi (with Sanskrit as part of the composite course); (b) Urdu or any other modern Indian language and (c) English or any other modern European language. In non-Hindi speaking States: (a) the regional language; (b) Hindi; (c) Urdu or any other modern Indian language excluding (a) and (b); and (d) English or any other modern European language\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-nic_1-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-nic-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Criticism\">Criticism</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Three-language_formula&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Criticism\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p><a href=\"/wiki/C._N._Annadurai\" title=\"C. N. Annadurai\">C. N. Annadurai</a>, then <a href=\"/wiki/Chief_Minister_of_Tamil_Nadu\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Chief Minister of Tamil Nadu\">Chief Minister of Tamil Nadu</a>, opposed the requirement to learn Hindi in Tamil Nadu, \"What serves to link us with the outside world is certainly capable of rendering the same service inside India as well. To plead for two link languages is like boring a smaller hole in a wall for the kitten while there is a bigger one for the cat. What suits the cat will suit the kitten as well.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Academics have noted the failure of the formula. Harold F. Schiffman, an expert on Dravidian culture at the <a href=\"/wiki/University_of_Pennsylvania\" title=\"University of Pennsylvania\">University of Pennsylvania</a>, observed that the formula \"has been honored in the breach more than in reality\" and that due the lack of a symbolic national language, there is a tendency \"for English to take over as the instrumental language\" in India.<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> Political scientist Brian Weinstein of <a href=\"/wiki/Howard_University\" title=\"Howard University\">Howard University</a> said that \"neither Hindi nor non-Hindi speaking states followed the (1968) directive\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-Weinstein_3-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Weinstein-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Three-language_formula&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-nic-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-nic_1-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-nic_1-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-nic_1-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://web.archive.org/web/20120222082907/http://www.education.nic.in/cd50years/u/47/3X/473X0I01.htm\">\"Three Language Formula\"</a>. Government Of India Ministry Of Human Resource Development Department Of Education. Archived from <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.education.nic.in/cd50years/u/47/3X/473X0I01.htm\">the original</a> on 22 February 2012<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">16 May</span> 2016</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Three+Language+Formula&amp;rft.pub=Government+Of+India+Ministry+Of+Human+Resource+Development+Department+Of+Education&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.education.nic.in%2Fcd50years%2Fu%2F47%2F3X%2F473X0I01.htm&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AThree-language+formula\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.academics-india.com/Radhakrishnan%20Commission%20Report%20of%201948-49.pdf\">\"Report of the University Education Commission (December 1948 \u2013 August 1949) Volume I\"</a> <span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(PDF)</span>. Ministry of Education, Government of India. 1962. p.&#160;280<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">16 May</span> 2016</span>. <q>Every boy and girl must obviously know the regional language, at the same time he should be acquainted with the Federal language, and should acquire the ability to read books in English.</q></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Report+of+the+University+Education+Commission+%28December+1948+%E2%80%93+August+1949%29+Volume+I&amp;rft.pages=280&amp;rft.pub=Ministry+of+Education%2C+Government+of+India&amp;rft.date=1962&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.academics-india.com%2FRadhakrishnan%2520Commission%2520Report%2520of%25201948-49.pdf&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AThree-language+formula\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Weinstein-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-Weinstein_3-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Weinstein_3-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Weinstein, Brian (1990). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=yrxjUJcgkHUC&amp;pg=PA95&amp;lpg=PA95&amp;q=graduated+three-language+formula\"><i>Language Policy and Political Development</i></a>. Greenwood Publishing Group. p.&#160;95. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/0-89391-611-0\" title=\"Special:BookSources/0-89391-611-0\">0-89391-611-0</a><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">16 May</span> 2016</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Language+Policy+and+Political+Development&amp;rft.pages=95&amp;rft.pub=Greenwood+Publishing+Group&amp;rft.date=1990&amp;rft.isbn=0-89391-611-0&amp;rft.aulast=Weinstein&amp;rft.aufirst=Brian&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.co.uk%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DyrxjUJcgkHUC%26pg%3DPA95%26lpg%3DPA95%26q%3Dgraduated%2Bthree-language%2Bformula&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AThree-language+formula\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.languageinindia.com/jan2009/gujralreport.html\">\"The Gujral Committee Report on Urdu\"</a>. <i>Language In India</i>. 8 May 1975<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">16 May</span> 2016</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=Language+In+India&amp;rft.atitle=The+Gujral+Committee+Report+on+Urdu&amp;rft.date=1975-05-08&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.languageinindia.com%2Fjan2009%2Fgujralreport.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AThree-language+formula\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-5\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://asiapacific.anu.edu.au/blogs/southasiamasala/2010/02/15/india-anna-and-the-dravidian-movement/\">\"Anna and the Dravidian Movement\"</a>. <i>South Asia Masala</i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">17 May</span> 2016</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=South+Asia+Masala&amp;rft.atitle=Anna+and+the+Dravidian+Movement&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fasiapacific.anu.edu.au%2Fblogs%2Fsouthasiamasala%2F2010%2F02%2F15%2Findia-anna-and-the-dravidian-movement%2F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AThree-language+formula\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-6\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-6\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\">Schiffman, Harold. <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://ccat.sas.upenn.edu/~haroldfs/540/handouts/indiapol/indic2.html\">\"Indian Linguistic Culture and the Genesis of Language Policy in the Subcontinent\"</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Indian+Linguistic+Culture+and+the+Genesis+of+Language+Policy+in+the+Subcontinent&amp;rft.aulast=Schiffman&amp;rft.aufirst=Harold&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fccat.sas.upenn.edu%2F~haroldfs%2F540%2Fhandouts%2Findiapol%2Findic2.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AThree-language+formula\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"External_links\">External links</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Three-language_formula&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: External links\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://web.archive.org/web/20030428023048/http://iqra-careers.com/c37a1.html\">\"Annexure 1: Three lan